Your `fizzBuzz` function has the right idea in terms of logic, but there are a few mistakes and inconsistencies in the code that need to be corrected.

1. You need to use `System.out.print` or `System.out.println` (uppercase 'S' and 'O') because it's case-sensitive.
2. The quotes you're using for the strings “FizzBuzz”, “Fizz”, and “Buzz” are not standard ASCII double quotes. Instead, they should be regular double quotes ("FizzBuzz", "Fizz", "Buzz").
3. You missed a semicolon `;` at the end of the `System.out.print(i)` call.
4. The loop should run until `n` instead of hardcoding the number 15 if you want to be able to control the number of iterations dynamically.
5. It's a good practice to include a space or a new line after each print statement for better readability; otherwise, the output will be one long, continuous line. `System.out.println` can be used to print each output on a new line, or you could append a space to the strings to separate the outputs.

Here is the corrected code:

```java
public static void fizzBuzz(int n) {
    // Write your code here
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        if (i % 3 == 0 && i % 5 == 0) {
            System.out.print("FizzBuzz ");
        } else if (i % 3 == 0) {
            System.out.print("Fizz ");
        } else if (i % 5 == 0) {
            System.out.print("Buzz ");
        } else {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
    }
}
```

To make it even more readable, consider using a newline character (`\n`) or `System.out.println`:

```java
public static void fizzBuzz(int n) {
    // Write your code here
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        if (i % 3 == 0 && i % 5 == 0) {
            System.out.println("FizzBuzz");
        } else if (i % 3 == 0) {
            System.out.println("Fizz");
        } else if (i % 5 == 0) {
            System.out.println("Buzz");
        } else {
            System.out.println(i);
        }
    }
}
```

This way, each output will be on its own line.
